  "prompt": "What is the difference between high fidelity and actual design?",
  "response": "High fidelity and actual design refer to different stages and aspects of the design process, particularly in user interface (UI) and user experience (UX) design.\n\n### High Fidelity Design\n\n**Definition:**\nHigh fidelity design refers to a polished and detailed representation of a product or interface that closely resembles the final outcome. It incorporates specific elements such as typography, colors, images, icons, and precise spacing.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- **Detailed Visuals:** High fidelity mockups showcase realistic layouts and visual styling.\n- **Interactivity:** They may include interactive elements that simulate how the final product will function, often created using tools like Figma, Sketch, or Adobe XD.\n- **User Testing:** High fidelity prototypes can be used for user testing to gather feedback on UI elements, flow, and design aesthetics.\n- **Client Presentation:** They are often used for presenting ideas to clients or stakeholders to get approval before moving into development.\n\n### Actual Design\n\n**Definition:**\nActual design refers to the final product that has been developed and deployed. This includes the completed system, application, or website that users interact with.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- **Functional Product:** Actual design is the fully developed version that has passed through all stages of the design and development process, including coding, testing, and deployment.\n- **User Experience:** This encompasses not just the visual layout but also the overall user experience, including performance, accessibility, and responsiveness.\n- **Iteration and Feedback:** Actual design may undergo further iterations based on real-world user feedback and analytics after launch.\n- **Integration:** The actual design involves integration with backend systems, databases, and any required APIs, ensuring everything works seamlessly.\n\n### Summary\n\nIn essence, high fidelity design is a detailed representation and prototype used primarily for visualization and testing before actual development, whereas actual design is the final, functional product that users experience. High fidelity serves as a blueprint and guide for the development of the actual design.",
